title: For Sale:  #4 Enfield "Irish Contract" - As good as it gets!!
postcontent:
For sale today is a pristine No.4 Mark II Enfield made in 1954. When I purchased this rifle many years ago it came to me "mummy" wrapped and oozing with cosmoline. It took me a couple of weekends to get it cleaned up as there was a surprising amount of cosmoline! It was literally packed into every nook & cranny. Looking back I probably should have kept it wrapped, but I just couldn't resist taking a look. Plus back then I had no idea then how rare and valuable this rifle really was.   

Anyway this one was made in December 1954 by Fazakerly as part of the so called "Irish Contract" that was never delivered. So these rifles sat in storage overseas for many years until some were eventually imported into the USA. I found this rifle at a gun show preview and it was the only one the dealer had. Since then I've attended countless other gun shows and I've never seen another one of these offered for sale. I do see them once every so often on GunBroker and they always sell quickly.   

This rifle is pristine with finish on metal and wood near 100%. I did shoot the rifle on several occasions but always cleaned it after firing so the bore is perfect as well. I spent much time gathering up all the accessories that go with the rifle and there isn't any one place where you can purchase everything I'm including. Some of these items are very tough to find today or are no longer available. So what I've assembled is somewhat of an "Enfield Collector's Dream". Even the ammo that's included is darn difficult to find today and while it all will go boom - I'd probably buy some recently manufactured ammo and hold onto what's included because it's bound to become more valuable.   

Included is the original #9 blade style bayonet that came with the rifle, plus an excellent original spike style bayonet with scabbard & frog. Also included is an original Enfield cleaning kit with bolt disassembly tool. An Enfield bandoleer with 10 stripper clips and 50 rounds of brass case surplus ammo. A heavy duty khaki canvas carry bag with a matching khaki color sling. Then the khaki green sling and  cover that came with the rifle.   

Finally there are (4) 32 round boxes of POF .303 ammo that is brass case and made in the 1960's plus an original 48 round box of British L1A1 .303 ball ammo.   

Asking price for the entire package is $1150. Pick up in Brandon by a Florida resident at least 21 years old.   

This package is a must to complete any Enfield collection. Thanks for looking.  

p.s. Forgot to say that every number on this rifle matches, even the magazine. The original bayonet is not numbered. The blade looks odd because the original protective tape is still on it.

title: For Sale:  Walther P99c AS 9mm
postcontent:
This pistol is barely used. Less than 100 rounds through it. Comes with factory fired shell, original papers, factory target, cleaning rod, 2 magazines, extra backstrap and original hard case. This pistol is in VERY good condition. This pistol being the "AS" model has a pretty neat trigger setup in it.

 "What sets the P99 trigger apart is it is a true traditional Double-Action/Single-Action mechanism that gives the feel of a DA/SA hammer-fired gun.  How it works:  When the magazine is inserted and the gun cocked, the trigger enters what is known as Anti-Stress mode.  The striker is fully cocked and ready to fire; however the trigger remains forward in the double action position.  Pulling the trigger now can be likened to a two-stage rifle trigger: a little under a half an inch of the trigger pull is slack, and at the end of the pull, the trigger will stop and suddenly experience an increase in pull to about 4.5 pounds.  The trigger break is very crisp with minimal over travel and a short reset of about 0.1 inch.  If fully released, the trigger will stop in its single action position, which has about half the take up of Anti-Stress mode."

Please contact me with any questions or potential trades. Please, no low end firearms as I am in the process of upgrading my collection.
